Project 2.¶

Facial Emotion Recognition Dataset: Understanding Human Expressions¶

This project was completed by Irina Maruna and Lucas Chapelle for DAT 402.

For this project we are using a "Facial Emotion Recognition Image Dataset" originally published on Kaggle:
https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sujaykapadnis/emotion-recognition-dataset?resource=download

Dataset Overview¶

This dataset contains images of human faces categorized into six distinct emotions:

  • Happy
  • Angry
  • Sad
  • Neutral
  • Surprise
  • Ahego (a nice expressive reaction)

Data Source & Collection¶

The images were acquired through various methods:

  • Social Media Scraping
  • YouTube Frames
  • Existing Datasets

Objective¶

The aim of this project is to apply machine learning techniques to:

  • Classify emotions
  • Analyze trends and common misclassifications in emotion recognition models
  • Evaluate different ML architectures, including deep learning methods like CNNs

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

Before training models, it's important to understand the dataset through visualizations and descriptive statistics.

1. Number of Images per Emotion Category¶

We count how many images are available for each emotion to understand class balance and identify any imbalance that could affect model performance.

In [40]:
from collections import defaultdict

# Create a dictionary to count the number of images per emotion category
image_counts = defaultdict(int)

# Loop through each emotion folder and count image files
for emotion in os.listdir(dataset_path):
    emotion_path = os.path.join(dataset_path, emotion)
    if os.path.isdir(emotion_path):
        image_counts[emotion] = len(os.listdir(emotion_path))

# Convert the counts into a DataFrame and sort by image count
image_counts_df = pd.DataFrame(list(image_counts.items()), columns=["Emotion", "Count"])
image_counts_df = image_counts_df.sort_values(by="Count", ascending=False)

# Display the result
print(image_counts_df)

2.Image Size Distribution¶

Before resizing images for modeling, it's helpful to explore their original dimensions. This analysis helps confirm whether images vary greatly in shape or resolution, and whether resizing (e.g., to 64×64) is appropriate.

In [15]:
from PIL import Image

image_sizes = []

# Loop through each emotion folder
for emotion in os.listdir(dataset_path):
    emotion_folder = os.path.join(dataset_path, emotion)
    if os.path.isdir(emotion_folder):
        for img_file in os.listdir(emotion_folder):
            img_path = os.path.join(emotion_folder, img_file)
            try:
                with Image.open(img_path) as img:
                    image_sizes.append(img.size)  # (width, height)
            except: # Skip corrupted or unreadable images
                pass 

# Convert image sizes into a DataFrame
size_df = pd.DataFrame(image_sizes, columns=["Width", "Height"])

# Plot histogram of image widths and heights
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.hist(size_df["Width"], bins=20, alpha=0.6, label='Width')
plt.hist(size_df["Height"], bins=20, alpha=0.6, label='Height')
plt.xlabel("Pixels")
plt.ylabel("Number of Images")
plt.title("Distribution of Image Widths and Heights")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observation¶

The majority of images have widths and heights under 500 pixels, but there is variation across the dataset. Resizing all images to a fixed size (e.g., 64×64) is necessary to standardize input for modeling and reduce computational complexity.

3.Class Balance Visualization¶

To better understand the distribution of emotion labels, we plot the number of images per category. Class imbalance can affect model learning — categories with fewer examples may be harder to classify correctly.

In [18]:

Observation

This bar plot shows the distribution of image counts across emotion categories. We observe a significant class imbalance:

  • 'Neutral', 'Sad', and 'Happy' have many more examples,
  • while 'Angry', 'Surprise', and 'Ahegao' are underrepresented.

This imbalance may impact the model's ability to classify minority emotions accurately.

Train/Test/Validation Split¶

To train and evaluate our model reliably, we divide the dataset into training and validation sets. We use TensorFlow’s ImageDataGenerator to handle both loading and preprocessing (like rescaling pixel values).

In [21]:
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

IMG_SIZE = (64, 64)
BATCH_SIZE = 32

# Create image data generator with normalization and validation split
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255, validation_split=0.3)

# Load training data (70% of total data)
train_generator = datagen.flow_from_directory(
    dataset_path,
    target_size=IMG_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='categorical',
    subset='training',
    shuffle=True
)

# Load validation data (30% of total data)
val_generator = datagen.flow_from_directory(
    dataset_path,
    target_size=IMG_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='categorical',
    subset='validation',
    shuffle=True
)

Build a CNN Model¶

We now define a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to classify facial expressions. CNNs are effective for image tasks because they learn spatial patterns such as edges, shapes, and textures.

In [27]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras import Input

# Define a simple CNN model architecture
model = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(64, 64, 3)),                 # Input layer: 64x64 RGB images
    # First Convolutional Block
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'),    # 32 filters, 3x3 kernel
    MaxPooling2D(2, 2),                       # # Downsample by 2x

    # Second Convolutional Block
    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),    # 64 filters
    MaxPooling2D(2, 2),

    # Flatten and Dense Layers
    Flatten(),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),            # Fully connected layer
    Dropout(0.5),                             # Prevent overfitting
    Dense(6, activation='softmax')            # Output layer (6 emotion classes)
])

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Summary
model.summary()

Observation

This table shows the structure of our CNN model. It includes two convolutional blocks followed by dense layers.

  • The model begins with two sets of Conv2D and MaxPooling2D layers. These layers help the model look at small parts of the image and learn shapes, lines, and patterns.
  • The Flatten layer turns the 2D feature maps into a 1D vector.
  • The Dense (128) layer is fully connected and learns more complex combinations of features.
  • A Dropout layer is used to prevent overfitting.
  • The final Dense (6) layer outputs the prediction probabilities for each of the 6 emotion categories.

The model has around 1.6 million trainable parameters, which means it's powerful enough to learn from a rich dataset like ours but still efficient to train.

Observation

Over the course of 10 training epochs, the model showed steady improvement in both training and validation accuracy.

  • Training accuracy increased from 32% to 76%, and the training loss dropped from 1.58 to 0.56, meaning the model learned better with each pass through the data.

  • Validation accuracy also rose from 49% to 65%, indicating the model is generalizing fairly well to unseen data and not just memorizing the training set.

This is a good sign that the model is learning useful patterns without heavily overfitting.

Evalution¶

1. Plot Accuracy and Loss¶

In [42]:
# Plot accuracy and loss over epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

# Accuracy Plot
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='Train Accuracy')
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Val Accuracy')
plt.title('Accuracy Over Epochs')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

# Loss Plot
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Train Loss')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Val Loss')
plt.title('Loss Over Epochs')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observation

The training accuracy gradually improves and reaches about 76% by the 10th epoch. The validation accuracy also increases, peaking around 65%, but doesn’t go much higher after that. This suggests the model is learning well but starts to overfit slightly - it gets better on training data than on new data.

Looking at the loss, the training loss consistently goes down, which is expected as the model learns. However, the validation loss drops at first, then starts to go up and down slightly, especially after epoch 4. This shows that while the model keeps improving on the training set, it has trouble improving on the validation set, likely because it’s starting to memorize the training data instead of learning general patterns.

3. Confusion Matrix¶

In [48]:
# Import tools for confusion matrix
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report
import seaborn as sns

# Get true and predicted labels
y_true = []
y_pred = []

val_generator.reset()
for i in range(len(val_generator)):
    x, y = val_generator[i]
    preds = model.predict(x)
    y_true.extend(np.argmax(y, axis=1))
    y_pred.extend(np.argmax(preds, axis=1))

# Get class names
class_names = list(val_generator.class_indices.keys())

# Confusion matrix Heatmap
cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', xticklabels=class_names, yticklabels=class_names, cmap="Blues")
plt.xlabel('Predicted')
plt.ylabel('True')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Classification report
print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=class_names))

Show Predictions (Correct vs Incorrect)¶

This step helps us better understand how the model performs on real validation images. By displaying both correct and incorrect predictions, we can visually inspect what the model is doing well and where it struggles.

In [52]:
# Get a batch from the validation set
x_val, y_val = next(val_generator)
y_pred = model.predict(x_val)

# Decode one-hot labels to class indices
true_labels = np.argmax(y_val, axis=1)
pred_labels = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)
class_names = list(val_generator.class_indices.keys())

# Plot 9 images with predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
for i in range(9):
    plt.subplot(3, 3, i+1)
    plt.imshow(x_val[i])
    true_class = class_names[true_labels[i]]
    pred_class = class_names[pred_labels[i]]
    color = 'green' if true_class == pred_class else 'red'
    plt.title(f"True: {true_class}\nPred: {pred_class}", color=color, fontsize=12)
    plt.axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.suptitle("Sample Predictions: Green = Correct, Red = Incorrect", fontsize=16, y=1.02)
plt.show()

Observation

he model correctly predicts many images, especially for clearer emotions like Happy or Ahegao. However, it sometimes confuses similar emotions - like Sad, Neutral, and Angry. This visual helps confirm the common errors seen in the confusion matrix and gives a quick view of where the model performs well or struggles.

Unsupervised Learning with PCA¶

We used PCA (Principal Component Analysis) to reduce the high-dimensional features from our CNN to 2D for visualization. This helps us better understand how the model “sees” and separates different emotions.

1. Rebuild CNN Using the Functional API¶

We rebuilt the CNN using the Functional API to better support feature extraction later for PCA.

In [56]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense, Dropout, Input

# Define input
input_layer = Input(shape=(64, 64, 3))

# Build the CNN layers
x = Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu')(input_layer)
x = MaxPooling2D(2, 2)(x)

x = Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu')(x)
x = MaxPooling2D(2, 2)(x)

x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)         # <-- we’ll extract features from here
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
output_layer = Dense(6, activation='softmax')(x)

# Now define the full model
model = Model(inputs=input_layer, outputs=output_layer)

# Compile
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Show summary
model.summary()

5. Apply PCA and Visualize¶

In [68]:
# Import PCA and visualization libraries
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# # Reduce the feature vectors to 2 principal components (for 2D visualization)
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
pca_result = pca.fit_transform(features_flat)

# Prepare true labels and class names
true_labels = np.argmax(y_batch, axis=1)
class_names = list(val_generator.class_indices.keys())

# Plot PCA results
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
for i, label in enumerate(np.unique(true_labels)):
    indices = true_labels == label    # Find all samples with the current label
    plt.scatter(pca_result[indices, 0], pca_result[indices, 1], label=class_names[label], alpha=0.6)

# Add plot labels and legend
plt.title("PCA Projection of CNN Features")
plt.xlabel("PCA Component 1")
plt.ylabel("PCA Component 2")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observation

The PCA projection shows how CNN features distribute emotions in 2D space. Most emotions, including Happy, Neutral, and Surprise, appear spread out with overlapping areas. This suggests the model captures some differences but also struggles to fully separate emotions, likely due to shared facial features between certain expressions.

Logistic Regression on CNN Features¶

In this section, we compare the deep learning approach with a classical machine learning model by applying Logistic Regression to features extracted from our CNN. By using these high-level, deep features as input, we evaluate how well a shallow classifier performs in predicting emotion classes, providing a useful baseline for comparison with our CNN model.

In [71]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# STEP 1: Prepare the data
# Use the same features and labels from your PCA block
X = features_flat  # extracted CNN features, already flattened
y = np.argmax(y_batch, axis=1)  # Convert one-hot to integer labels

# STEP 2: Fit Logistic Regression
# Solver 'lbfgs' works well for small-medium datasets
log_model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)
log_model.fit(X, y)

# STEP 3: Predict and evaluate
y_pred_lr = log_model.predict(X)

# Accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y, y_pred_lr)
print(f"Logistic Regression Accuracy on PCA Features: {accuracy:.2f}")

# Detailed report
print(classification_report(y, y_pred_lr, target_names=class_names, zero_division=0))

Observation

Logistic Regression using the PCA-reduced CNN features achieved only 44% accuracy and mostly predicted "Neutral" for all samples. This suggests that while CNN extracted rich representations, reducing them to just two dimensions loses too much information for simpler models like Logistic Regression to work effectively.

Conclusion¶

In this project, we built a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to classify facial emotions into six categories. The model reached 76% training accuracy and 65% validation accuracy. While it learned useful patterns, the validation loss stopped improving and slightly increased, showing signs of overfitting. The confusion matrix and metrics showed good results for "Happy" and "Neutral," but emotions like "Angry" and "Surprise" were harder to predict.

To better understand what the CNN learned, we used PCA to reduce features to two dimensions. The PCA plot showed some weak clusters, but there was still a lot of overlap between classes. We also tried Logistic Regression on the PCA features, which gave poor results (44% accuracy), mostly predicting only "Neutral." This showed that the compressed features were not enough for simpler models.

Overall, the CNN worked well for this task, but traditional models struggled when using reduced feature sets.
